% of seniors having at least basic digital skills:
 28% acc.: https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/statistics-explained/index.php?oldid=627685
 34% men, 25% women, acc.: https://ec.europa.eu/eurostat/web/products-eurostat-news/w/ddn-20240222-1
 24% acc.: https://unece.org/media/press/358156
44% of seniors say they don’t need help → they have at least basic digital skills: link
40% in the age group of 55 to 64, 24% in the age group of 65 to 74: https://www.un.org/development/desa/ageing/wp-content/uploads/sites/24/2022/06/Technologies-and-older-persons-by-Ana-Maria-Carrillo-Soubic.pdf
33% of people aged 75 & over in the UK and 13% of people aged 65 to 74 in the UK, do not have the skills required to thrive in a digital society in day-to-day life: https://www.ageuk.org.uk/siteassets/documents/reports-and-publications/reports-and-briefings/active-communities/internet-use-statistics-june-2024.pdf

How big number of people needs to help his parents with digital activities
More than half (52 per cent) would ask their kids for help if they needed assistance with something (online banking), while five per cent would just give up: https://abilitynet.org.uk/news-blogs/survey-reveals-what-older-people-want-do-tech#:~:text=More%20than%20half%20,cent%20would%20just%20give%20up
Almost half of seniors (47%) need help using digital devices, and most often this support comes from their children or grandchildren. Among those receiving help, 84% find it useful: https://www.ageuk.org.uk/bp-assets/globalassets/redbridge-barking--havering/voe/age-uk-rbh---digital-skills-survey-2023-full-report.pdf#:~:text=Practical%20Support%20%E2%80%A2%20Just%20under,have%20not
Almost all seniors in the study reported relying on their children or grandchildren for help with technology: https://aging.jmir.org/2019/1/e13713/


How big number of people go to U3A
 In GB over 1000 u3as with around 400,000 members, acc.: https://www.u3a.org.uk/about ; https://cupar.u3asite.uk/history-of-the-national-u3a/ ; 
(GB) There are 1,057 u3as with over 450,000 members, acc.: https://www.nottshelpyourself.org.uk/kb5/nottinghamshire/directory/service.page?=&id=1sDpEy0Mers ; https://seaton.u3asite.uk/wp-content/uploads/2024/07/u3ahistoryandstructure.pdf
Over 1,000 U3As (400,000 members) at the end of 2017, acc.: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/336702123_Universities_of_The_Third_Age
In Australia, there are more than 300 local U3As, with a total membership exceeding 100,000 people: https://ala.asn.au/stories/u3a-40-years-of-lifelong-learning-connections-and-friendships/ ; https://www.researchgate.net/publication/336702123_Universities_of_The_Third_Age
New Zealand held 84 U3As which included some 4,000 members at the end of 2017: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/336702123_Universities_of_The_Third_Age
In the Asian continent, China alone included 60,867 U3As and around 7,643,100 members in 2015: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/336702123_Universities_of_The_Third_Age

How big number of people go any digital skills trainings
Around half of respondents (46%) would like help to improve their digital skills: link

How big number of senior have enough money
In the USA, most households aged 65+ report median incomes of around $50–55 k per year: https://pensionrights.org/resource/income-of-todays-older-adults
In FYE 2023, the average income after  costs was £387 per week. Single pensioners had £267 per week, while pensioner couples had £561 per week: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/pensioners-incomes-financial-years-ending-1995-to-2023/pensioners-incomes-financial-years-ending-1995-to-2023
According to Statistics Canada’s 2024 Canadian Income Survey, the average after‑tax retirement income for senior families in 2022 was $74,200. For individual seniors, it was $33,600: https://www.fidelity.ca/en/insights/articles/what-is-the-average-retirement-income-in-canada/
The national median weekly personal income across Australia was $789, and the median weekly household income was $1,770: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demographics_of_Australia ; https://www.abs.gov.au/articles/new-census-insights-income-australia-using-administrative-data

How big amount of seniors have family who have money
less than 7% of older people receive money: https://webfs.oecd.org/els-com/Family_Database/PF_1_7_Intergenerational_solidarity.pdf
(USA) only9% of those age 50 and over received cash support from their relatives: https://webfs.oecd.org/els-com/Family_Database/PF_1_7_Intergenerational_solidarity.pdf
Financial support from adult children to parents in Europe is very rare (0.4–3.6%): https://population-europe.eu/research/popdigests/caring-older-parents-it-matter-social-norms
On average, 60% of people aged 65+ in OECD countries receive support from family or friends: https://www.mdpi.com/2076-0760/14/1/44
Globally, only about 5% of adult children provide parents with financial support (>200 USD), while 16% offer other types of help: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S2666558123000507
(Korea) In Korea, by contrast, 41% of older people received cash from their children, much higher than in other countries: https://webfs.oecd.org/els-com/Family_Database/PF_1_7_Intergenerational_solidarity.pdf

Other:
91% regularly use a mobile phone, and 56% of over-65s are users of a tablet: https://abilitynet.org.uk/news-blogs/survey-reveals-what-older-people-want-do-tech#:~:text=More%20than%20half%20,cent%20would%20just%20give%20up
In the UK, online U3A membership costs £12 per year (about £1 per month): https://www.u3a.org.uk/get-involved/join
(Slovakia) The Tablet Project aims at training 105,440 seniors in digital skills: https://www.oecd.org/content/dam/oecd/en/about/programmes/dg-reform/slovak-republic/Implementation-Roadmap-for-Enhancing-the-Digital-Skills-of-Seniors-in-the-Slovak-Republic.pdf
Currently, only 55.6% of adults in the EU have at least basic digital skills, far from the EU’s 2030 target of 80%: https://joint-research-centre.ec.europa.eu/jrc-news-and-updates/how-reach-eu-target-80-adults-basic-digital-skills-2030-2025-03-05_en

